WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.220
Okay, so this may look familiar to some of you.

00:00:03.220 --> 00:00:05.220
It is what I lovingly refer to

00:00:05.220 --> 00:00:08.060
as the Project Folder Hellscape.

00:00:08.060 --> 00:00:10.040
Looking at it, it's chaotic.

00:00:10.040 --> 00:00:12.140
There's a lot of different folders

00:00:12.140 --> 00:00:14.420
with not very informative names.

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:16.059
There's a lot of different files,

00:00:16.059 --> 00:00:18.340
a lot of different versions of the same file,

00:00:18.340 --> 00:00:22.740
and a lot of files that have really uninformative names,

00:00:22.740 --> 00:00:25.780
like MD7, I have no idea what that means.

00:00:25.780 --> 00:00:28.860
And at one point or another, when doing this project,

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:32.540
this was from my PhD, I asked myself,

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:34.060
where is that script?

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:36.580
And which file is current?

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:39.299
And what was I thinking months ago?

00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:42.419
And I'm sure some of you can relate to this.

00:00:42.419 --> 00:00:44.820
And so after I finished my PhD,

00:00:44.820 --> 00:00:47.299
and I moved on to a postdoc,

00:00:47.299 --> 00:00:50.380
I started to think, okay, how can I do this better?

00:00:50.380 --> 00:00:52.580
How can I move away from this chaotic

00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:56.700
Project Folder Hellscape into something more organized?

00:00:56.700 --> 00:00:58.500
And so what if I told you that I found

00:00:59.139 --> 00:01:02.660
that better way, that I could turn this chaos

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:06.459
into a nice, organized file structure

00:01:06.459 --> 00:01:09.160
that I could use for every code-based project?

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:12.739
So you may ask, how?

00:01:12.739 --> 00:01:16.620
Well, by structuring your project as an R package.

00:01:20.620 --> 00:01:22.019
Thank you.

00:01:22.019 --> 00:01:25.239
And I don't mean from the software development perspective,

00:01:25.239 --> 00:01:27.580
where the primary goal of the project

00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:31.779
is to end up with a production-ready R package.

00:01:31.779 --> 00:01:35.220
I mean by using the actual file structure

00:01:35.220 --> 00:01:36.940
of an R packaging package,

00:01:36.940 --> 00:01:39.339
and leveraging the benefits of an R package

00:01:39.339 --> 00:01:41.900
to better organize, document,

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:44.660
and ultimately share your code.

00:01:44.660 --> 00:01:46.540
And so for the rest of this talk,

00:01:46.540 --> 00:01:50.260
I wanna walk you through how I've used this workflow,

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:52.940
and I wanna provide you with examples

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:55.620
of tangible impacts that it's had on my work.

00:01:55.620 --> 00:01:58.419
And so in order to give you a little bit of context

00:01:58.419 --> 00:02:01.339
for one of the project I've used this approach on,

00:02:01.339 --> 00:02:02.940
we need to travel back in time.

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:07.279
Back to June of 2021 in the Netherlands.

00:02:07.279 --> 00:02:11.720
Now, I'm sorry, we all know what was happening in 2021.

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:15.660
The COVID pandemic was in full swing.

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:18.720
And the Netherlands had actually already experienced

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:22.779
multiple waves of infections denoted here by the blue line,

00:02:22.779 --> 00:02:26.779
which shows daily new confirmed COVID-19 cases over time.

00:02:26.779 --> 00:02:28.740
But things were looking up.

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:31.220
COVID-19 cases were decreasing,

00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:33.539
vaccination was ongoing in adults,

00:02:33.539 --> 00:02:37.039
and strict control measures were gradually being relaxed.

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:39.660
But the Dutch government was obviously concerned

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:43.300
with how best to continue relaxing control measures

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:45.860
while preventing future waves of infections.

00:02:45.860 --> 00:02:48.520
And one of the ways that they were thinking of doing this

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:53.160
was by extending the vaccination campaign

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:54.619
to adolescents and children.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:57.899
And so this is where I come in.

00:02:57.899 --> 00:03:01.119
In my role, I was asked to do a modeling study

00:03:01.119 --> 00:03:02.720
to try to determine the impacts

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:05.240
of extending the vaccination campaign

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:06.800
to adolescents and children,

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:09.600
and to try to tell them what impact that might have

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:13.600
on disease outcomes like infections and hospitalizations.

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:16.119
And so that is your context.

00:03:16.119 --> 00:03:17.479
So for the remainder of the talk,

00:03:17.479 --> 00:03:20.039
I'm gonna go through each of those steps

00:03:20.039 --> 00:03:21.899
of the R package structure,

00:03:21.899 --> 00:03:24.000
and I'm gonna keep coming back to this project

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.679
and show you how using this workflow

00:03:26.679 --> 00:03:28.479
helped me perform this work.

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:31.279
So the first step is organize.

00:03:31.279 --> 00:03:33.679
So in a typical project, you have different types of files.

00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:36.639
You may have analysis scripts, data,

00:03:36.639 --> 00:03:38.279
maybe some R functions,

00:03:38.279 --> 00:03:40.320
and maybe some kind of documentation.

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:43.160
And every person has different ways

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:44.320
of organizing their projects.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:46.660
And even the same person may have different ways

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:48.860
of organizing different projects.

00:03:48.860 --> 00:03:51.619
And that can make it very difficult

00:03:51.619 --> 00:03:53.820
to orient yourself within any given project.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:57.020
But by using the R package structure,

00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:59.020
now all of a sudden you have a consistent way

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:01.580
in which to organize every single project,

00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:05.979
and every type of file has its own place.

00:04:05.979 --> 00:04:09.779
So your function files will go in the R directory,

00:04:09.779 --> 00:04:13.580
your analysis scripts and data can go in the inst directory,

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:15.580
and documentation can go in vignettes.

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:17.420
And actually, when you build the package,

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:20.179
R will yell at you if these are not in the right place.

00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:25.859
And so with this organization comes more efficiency,

00:04:25.859 --> 00:04:28.299
which was paramount in my work during the pandemic

00:04:28.299 --> 00:04:31.299
because we did not have a lot of time to do this work.

00:04:31.299 --> 00:04:33.799
And so I was able to orient myself and work efficiently,

00:04:33.799 --> 00:04:36.140
which meant that I could update models rapidly

00:04:36.140 --> 00:04:40.059
as new data became available, which it did consistently.

00:04:40.059 --> 00:04:42.679
It meant that the analysis was delivered on time.

00:04:42.679 --> 00:04:46.399
And so ultimately, my work was actually used

00:04:46.399 --> 00:04:49.239
to directly inform public health policy decisions,

00:04:49.239 --> 00:04:51.600
and the Dutch government did ultimately decide

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:53.399
to extend the vaccination campaign,

00:04:53.399 --> 00:04:55.980
which affected over a million citizens.

00:04:57.399 --> 00:05:00.339
But organization alone is not enough.

00:05:00.339 --> 00:05:04.359
We need to be able to understand how, what, and why

00:05:04.359 --> 00:05:07.000
we're doing aspects of a project.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.059
And so let's go back to that old file structure.

00:05:10.059 --> 00:05:12.700
So here we have a number of different documentation files,

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:15.179
maybe a code guide, maybe some description

00:05:15.179 --> 00:05:17.980
of the methodology that the code is implementing,

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:20.140
and maybe a final report.

00:05:20.140 --> 00:05:24.059
And it can be very hard to have a separate text file

00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:27.220
in a repo that describes what the code is doing.

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:30.660
I once inherited a project where I was given

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:34.299
a repository of code and an academic manuscript.

00:05:34.299 --> 00:05:36.579
The code was uncommented, undocumented,

00:05:36.579 --> 00:05:38.779
and all I had to go off of was a method section

00:05:38.779 --> 00:05:39.899
in an academic manuscript.

00:05:40.739 --> 00:05:42.220
And if you've ever read an academic manuscript,

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:44.779
they are notoriously concise.

00:05:44.779 --> 00:05:47.059
So I had a very small method section

00:05:47.059 --> 00:05:49.940
with which to try to decipher the code I was looking at.

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:52.859
And it ended up, I had to end up rerunning all the code

00:05:52.859 --> 00:05:54.100
and looking at intermediate results

00:05:54.100 --> 00:05:55.500
to try to figure out what was going on.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:57.459
And that took a lot of time.

00:05:57.459 --> 00:06:00.220
But with an R package, you have the advantage

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:02.899
that documentation lives with the code.

00:06:02.899 --> 00:06:05.579
And I want to highlight two important features

00:06:05.579 --> 00:06:07.579
of R package documentation.

00:06:07.579 --> 00:06:10.260
The first will be the automatically generated help files,

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:12.540
which gets stored in the man directory.

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:13.980
And the second are vignettes.

00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:21.179
So if you use the ROxygen, or ROxygen, not really sure,

00:06:21.179 --> 00:06:23.179
preamble above your function,

00:06:23.179 --> 00:06:25.459
you can include really important information

00:06:25.459 --> 00:06:27.839
about what that function is doing,

00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:31.859
like what that function does, expected inputs,

00:06:31.859 --> 00:06:35.179
expected outputs, and example usage.

00:06:35.179 --> 00:06:37.820
And a really nice piece of this

00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:41.440
is that this preamble lives with your function code.

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:43.940
So you can write this as your coding.

00:06:43.940 --> 00:06:45.880
So it alleviates the problem

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:47.339
of having to write a bunch of code

00:06:47.339 --> 00:06:50.220
and then go back a week, two weeks, a month later

00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:52.700
and try to remember what you did and describe it.

00:06:52.700 --> 00:06:56.399
So this way, you can document your code in real time.

00:06:56.399 --> 00:06:58.839
The other very handy aspect of this preamble

00:06:58.839 --> 00:07:00.579
is that when you build the package,

00:07:00.579 --> 00:07:03.459
it creates automatically generated help files.

00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:06.940
And so now, you can access this information

00:07:06.940 --> 00:07:08.500
by running one line of code,

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:10.380
the question mark and function name.

00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:12.339
So you don't have to go searching

00:07:12.339 --> 00:07:13.920
through some sort of project directory

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:15.500
to find the information that you need

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:18.899
in order to run a function or use a code chunk.

00:07:18.899 --> 00:07:20.700
It is easy to access.

00:07:22.700 --> 00:07:25.980
And so you may actually find that by using these help files

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:28.500
that you don't need that code guide anymore.

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:30.820
That maybe you don't need a piece of documentation

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:33.059
that you would in a more traditional project.

00:07:33.859 --> 00:07:37.399
And that's one less thing to have to update and manage.

00:07:38.459 --> 00:07:41.380
And the second part of documentation

00:07:41.380 --> 00:07:43.500
that I wanna touch on is the vignettes.

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:45.119
So I have only recently realized

00:07:45.119 --> 00:07:47.579
how powerful these vignettes can be.

00:07:47.579 --> 00:07:50.220
So you remember that project where I had a code base

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:52.600
and a methods paragraph?

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:57.100
With a vignette, you can actually incorporate text,

00:07:57.100 --> 00:07:59.260
code and results.

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:00.920
So now all of a sudden,

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:04.399
I can actually describe what a code chunk is doing,

00:08:04.399 --> 00:08:07.959
show the code chunk and then show the expected output.

00:08:07.959 --> 00:08:10.200
And that's hugely beneficial

00:08:10.200 --> 00:08:11.899
and it makes it much easier

00:08:11.899 --> 00:08:14.720
to try to document a whole analysis.

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:17.179
The other really nice feature of a vignette

00:08:17.179 --> 00:08:19.000
is that it can be version controlled

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:20.880
in the same way as your code.

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:23.000
So whereas if you have a Word file,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.880
that Word file is being tracked via words track changes

00:08:26.880 --> 00:08:28.739
and it's separate from your code.

00:08:28.779 --> 00:08:30.299
So it increases the likelihood

00:08:30.299 --> 00:08:32.739
that those two documents are gonna be out of sync.

00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:36.500
With a vignette, it can also be version controlled

00:08:36.500 --> 00:08:37.940
using GitHub like your code

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:40.260
and so it just makes the likelihood

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:42.880
of the documentation file and the code file

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:44.940
becoming out of sync much lower.

00:08:44.940 --> 00:08:46.380
Can still happen, you still have to update

00:08:46.380 --> 00:08:49.340
your documentation, but it increases the chance

00:08:49.340 --> 00:08:51.119
that your documentation is current.

00:08:52.739 --> 00:08:54.940
And so with the vignette, you may actually find

00:08:54.940 --> 00:08:58.380
that you don't need a separate methodology document

00:08:59.020 --> 00:09:01.219
and that maybe all you need is a final report.

00:09:03.299 --> 00:09:05.260
And so with all this increased documentation

00:09:05.260 --> 00:09:06.619
comes transparency.

00:09:06.619 --> 00:09:10.340
And transparency is important in all projects

00:09:10.340 --> 00:09:13.340
and particularly those that inform decision making.

00:09:13.340 --> 00:09:16.159
And in the context of the COVID-19 vaccination,

00:09:17.020 --> 00:09:19.859
this meant that the policy decisions

00:09:19.859 --> 00:09:21.700
were being backed by transparent analysis

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:24.940
and this became extremely important because we were audited.

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:28.340
So the modeling work that I and my team did

00:09:29.179 --> 00:09:30.020
during the pandemic was audited

00:09:30.020 --> 00:09:32.059
by an international panel of experts

00:09:32.059 --> 00:09:34.859
and they asked, why did you do this

00:09:34.859 --> 00:09:36.340
at various points of times?

00:09:36.340 --> 00:09:37.419
What assumptions did you make?

00:09:37.419 --> 00:09:38.739
Why did you make those?

00:09:38.739 --> 00:09:41.340
And because I used this approach, my work was traceable.

00:09:41.340 --> 00:09:43.419
I could go back and say, I made that decision

00:09:43.419 --> 00:09:45.640
because that was the information that we had at that time

00:09:45.640 --> 00:09:48.140
and then we got new information on and on and on.

00:09:49.219 --> 00:09:51.440
A second feature was that the public could understand

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:54.140
the scientific basis for the decisions that were being made

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:58.140
which was really, really critical in a global emergency

00:09:58.940 --> 00:09:59.979
because governments were asking their citizens

00:09:59.979 --> 00:10:01.700
to make extraordinary changes to their lives

00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:04.299
and it was very frustrating for people to not understand

00:10:04.299 --> 00:10:05.739
why they were being asked to do that

00:10:05.739 --> 00:10:08.979
and just having to rely on the model.

00:10:08.979 --> 00:10:11.900
And so this ultimately helped build more public trust

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:14.140
and you can think about the public in this sense

00:10:14.140 --> 00:10:16.419
as my ultimate stakeholder.

00:10:16.419 --> 00:10:18.659
And so imagine how this could build trust

00:10:18.659 --> 00:10:21.299
with whatever stakeholders you're working with.

00:10:22.859 --> 00:10:26.619
And so the first two features of this R package workflow

00:10:26.619 --> 00:10:29.340
focus mainly on your individual workflow,

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:31.859
how you move through a project.

00:10:31.859 --> 00:10:36.859
But what I think makes the R package really powerful

00:10:37.159 --> 00:10:38.260
is that when you combine it

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:40.859
with some sort of file sharing platform,

00:10:40.859 --> 00:10:43.059
whether that's GitHub or a shared network drive

00:10:43.059 --> 00:10:45.500
or something, then all of a sudden

00:10:45.500 --> 00:10:48.280
you have collaborative magic.

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:52.380
Because now all of a sudden you have this beautiful,

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:55.859
organized, standardized, documented,

00:10:55.859 --> 00:10:58.299
for lack of a better word, package,

00:10:58.299 --> 00:11:00.820
that enables you to install it easily.

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:04.219
So rather than having to source a bunch of separate scripts,

00:11:04.219 --> 00:11:07.700
you can install a package in one line of code.

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:10.599
You also have a way to have seamless handovers.

00:11:10.599 --> 00:11:14.659
So it becomes very easy for you to onboard a new person

00:11:14.659 --> 00:11:16.940
or even for yourself to come back to a project

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:17.960
after six months.

00:11:18.979 --> 00:11:20.840
Another important feature is that you can create

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:23.260
reusable tools that you and your colleagues

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:25.840
and other people at your organization can use.

00:11:26.679 --> 00:11:28.880
So I found out in my team that actually me

00:11:28.880 --> 00:11:30.599
and two other colleagues were all trying

00:11:30.599 --> 00:11:31.440
to use the same method

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:33.840
and we were independently coding that.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:37.099
But with this approach, someone can code it one time

00:11:37.099 --> 00:11:38.880
and we can all use it.

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:41.239
And this is also really important in infectious disease work

00:11:41.239 --> 00:11:44.159
because I realized that I'm lucky enough

00:11:44.159 --> 00:11:46.760
to have the resources to build these tools.

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:48.799
That is not the case everywhere.

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:52.780
And it's very important that everyone has the capability

00:11:52.780 --> 00:11:54.979
and the resources and the tools

00:11:54.979 --> 00:11:57.940
with which to analyze their own data.

00:11:57.940 --> 00:12:01.039
And finally, it facilitates collaboration.

00:12:01.039 --> 00:12:02.940
So it's one thing to have a conversation

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:05.380
with someone outside your organization

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:08.539
or someone on another team about things you're working on,

00:12:08.539 --> 00:12:11.700
but it changes the game when you're able to show them

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:13.859
what you're working on and generate ideas

00:12:13.859 --> 00:12:16.380
for how you can either work on the current project

00:12:16.380 --> 00:12:17.900
or extend it later.

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:21.659
And so with all of this sharing capability

00:12:21.659 --> 00:12:24.000
comes reproducibility, which is a central principle

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:25.359
in scientific research.

00:12:26.479 --> 00:12:30.799
And how this manifested during the COVID modeling

00:12:30.799 --> 00:12:32.479
was that because I use this approach,

00:12:32.479 --> 00:12:35.340
my model code was actually selected to be included

00:12:35.340 --> 00:12:37.679
in a separate R package called Epidemics,

00:12:37.679 --> 00:12:39.780
which serves as a transmission model library.

00:12:39.780 --> 00:12:43.000
So they were able to take my code, make it better,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.479
and include it in this other package for others to use.

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:49.400
Another thing was that I was able to be involved

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:54.400
in a European-wide effort to provide modeling results

00:12:54.679 --> 00:12:58.440
to help inform COVID public health policy.

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:00.159
And that would have been much more difficult

00:13:00.159 --> 00:13:01.640
if I hadn't used this approach.

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:04.099
And so ultimately, one national analysis

00:13:04.099 --> 00:13:06.400
has now become a piece of international infrastructure

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:09.400
that will live beyond the work that I did.

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:13.200
And so now it's your turn.

00:13:13.200 --> 00:13:16.099
I really encourage you to try using an R package structure

00:13:16.099 --> 00:13:17.080
for your next project.

00:13:17.080 --> 00:13:18.880
And if you're a little intimidated,

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:20.400
you've never made an R package,

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:22.179
there are some wonderful tools

00:13:22.179 --> 00:13:23.940
and learning materials available.

00:13:23.940 --> 00:13:25.400
And I want to point to two.

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:26.799
So one is the uses package,

00:13:26.799 --> 00:13:29.159
which actually makes creating the R package structure

00:13:29.159 --> 00:13:30.559
really, really easy.

00:13:30.559 --> 00:13:33.500
And then the other is the R packages book,

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:36.539
which gives you details about every step of the process,

00:13:36.539 --> 00:13:39.440
including some that I haven't even mentioned like testing.

00:13:40.500 --> 00:13:42.760
And I promise you'll never go back to messy folders.

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:45.520
And I'm also happy to announce

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:47.760
that after years of sort of using this approach

00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:50.440
and iteratively improving,

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:53.200
that I've just had my first package accepted to CRAN.

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:54.719
And I don't know that that would have been possible

00:13:54.719 --> 00:13:55.559
without this.

00:13:55.559 --> 00:14:00.219
So with that, I would be happy to take your questions

00:14:00.219 --> 00:14:02.119
and please feel free to get in touch.

00:14:03.020 --> 00:14:05.000
Thank you so much, Kylie.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.159
We have a few questions here.

00:14:07.159 --> 00:14:09.039
So the first one is,

00:14:09.039 --> 00:14:11.039
are there any parts of the package workflow

00:14:11.039 --> 00:14:13.400
you've needed to work around for this use case

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:14.500
to work well for you?

00:14:16.039 --> 00:14:19.119
Yes.

00:14:19.119 --> 00:14:22.919
So I'm gonna answer a slightly different question

00:14:22.919 --> 00:14:24.159
in a way to answer that question.

00:14:24.159 --> 00:14:27.320
So one of the things that I think a lot of people think of

00:14:27.320 --> 00:14:29.880
when they start thinking about R packages and documentation

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:32.239
is that it costs time.

00:14:32.239 --> 00:14:34.960
It costs time in order to do these different bits

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:39.440
that you may not invest in a different workflow.

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:43.479
And so there were times where we maybe had to focus more

00:14:43.479 --> 00:14:45.559
on just getting the analysis results

00:14:45.559 --> 00:14:47.299
and kind of tackle the documentation later

00:14:47.299 --> 00:14:49.840
because we were under such tight timelines.

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:53.200
But ideally you'd be able to do both kind of together.

00:14:54.479 --> 00:14:55.400
Amazing.

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:57.239
Yeah, we have quite a few here.

00:14:57.239 --> 00:14:59.239
So I'm gonna get through them.

00:14:59.239 --> 00:15:01.799
So how do you deal with multiple versions of data

00:15:01.799 --> 00:15:02.719
or programs?

00:15:06.159 --> 00:15:08.080
So the way that I dealt with it,

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:13.039
because like I said, we got new data all the time.

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:17.280
And I actually kept copies of the data,

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:19.320
different versions of the data

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:22.640
because I needed to be able to reproduce the model results

00:15:22.640 --> 00:15:23.840
at a given time.

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:28.080
So I actually kept them in a data directory in the package.

00:15:30.200 --> 00:15:31.119
Totally makes sense.

00:15:31.119 --> 00:15:34.159
So do you have any recommendations for implementing

00:15:34.159 --> 00:15:36.400
a shared package development workflow

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:38.599
when PHI is a factor

00:15:38.599 --> 00:15:41.359
and online tools like GitHub aren't allowed?

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:43.919
Can you define PHI?

00:15:43.919 --> 00:15:44.799
I wish I could.

00:15:44.799 --> 00:15:47.799
It is a private health information.

00:15:47.799 --> 00:15:48.640
Oh, private health.

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:50.760
Yeah, so that is one thing that I didn't mention

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:55.640
that obviously some of this can't be shared publicly.

00:15:55.640 --> 00:15:57.719
Many of us work on projects where you can't share this.

00:15:57.719 --> 00:16:00.760
In fact, I couldn't share this work publicly at first.

00:16:00.760 --> 00:16:04.880
It had to be shown to the government and approved

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:07.000
and then it could be shared.

00:16:07.239 --> 00:16:11.559
But I actually, my team works on GitLab,

00:16:11.559 --> 00:16:13.039
which is in a secure environment.

00:16:13.039 --> 00:16:15.880
And so this works fine within a secure environment.

00:16:15.880 --> 00:16:19.520
As long as the team members are able to access

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:22.320
some sort of shared environment, it works really well.

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:23.880
Great.

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:25.679
What would you have done differently now

00:16:25.679 --> 00:16:28.719
after seeing the European consortium changes to your code?

00:16:30.039 --> 00:16:33.239
Oh, I would have done a ton of things differently.

00:16:33.239 --> 00:16:36.440
I would have changed how I designed the whole model,

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:39.080
but I had about two weeks to create it.

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:40.799
And so it was just kind of like, all right,

00:16:40.799 --> 00:16:42.559
just put something that works.

00:16:42.559 --> 00:16:44.840
And that's funny because that was also a question

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:46.159
asked by the auditor.

00:16:47.159 --> 00:16:49.719
But yeah, I would have made it more efficient,

00:16:49.719 --> 00:16:54.719
but that's just, it was a fact of the situation.

00:16:56.799 --> 00:16:58.039
How does your workflow work

00:16:58.039 --> 00:17:00.280
with computationally heavy simulations?

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:04.280
Yeah, that's a good one.

00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:05.880
So I don't actually do a lot

00:17:05.880 --> 00:17:09.160
of computationally intensive simulations.

00:17:09.160 --> 00:17:12.359
I was able to get it quite quick.

00:17:13.479 --> 00:17:15.839
But I think what you can do is if you have the resources

00:17:15.839 --> 00:17:19.319
to use some sort of high performance computing,

00:17:19.319 --> 00:17:21.959
you can have the functionality within the package

00:17:21.959 --> 00:17:24.719
and then you just run those simulations elsewhere.

00:17:24.719 --> 00:17:26.920
But I don't think this would prevent you

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:29.239
from having the code in which to do something

00:17:29.239 --> 00:17:30.959
that's computationally intensive.

00:17:30.959 --> 00:17:31.800
Right.

00:17:32.359 --> 00:17:35.479
Do you have any recommendations

00:17:35.479 --> 00:17:37.000
for getting teammates on board

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.400
with this very different way of setting up projects,

00:17:39.400 --> 00:17:42.040
especially with folks who are already resistant

00:17:42.040 --> 00:17:44.439
to putting time into documentation?

00:17:44.439 --> 00:17:45.479
Yes.

00:17:45.479 --> 00:17:48.239
So I feel like this was asked by one of my colleagues.

00:17:48.239 --> 00:17:49.400
I have struggled a lot

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:51.119
because I think they're tired of me talking about this

00:17:51.119 --> 00:17:54.439
at work, but I'm finally making headway.

00:17:54.439 --> 00:17:59.079
And basically I keep sort of showing them

00:17:59.079 --> 00:18:02.319
the benefits of this and highlighting pain points

00:18:02.319 --> 00:18:06.599
when it's not done and in gentle ways,

00:18:06.599 --> 00:18:08.599
not like yelling at people.

00:18:08.599 --> 00:18:11.359
But I do think showing how easy it can be

00:18:11.359 --> 00:18:14.199
and how ultimately it can save time,

00:18:14.199 --> 00:18:16.079
because that's always a consideration that,

00:18:16.079 --> 00:18:18.520
oh, no, it's more work to make documentation.

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:20.599
But in the end, it will actually save you time

00:18:20.599 --> 00:18:25.359
and make it easier for work to be done.

00:18:25.359 --> 00:18:26.199
Amazing.

00:18:26.199 --> 00:18:27.199
Thank you so much.

00:18:27.199 --> 00:18:28.040
Thank you.

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:28.880
Thank you.

